ProductTitle: Intel Core I7-13700K Processor 30M Cache, Up to 5.40 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewTitle: It heats up, it's not cheap, but it pushes hard
ReviewContent: I changed my configuration recently and I switched from an i5-7600k to this i7-13700k model... Needless to say, it's quite unusual. I installed it on an Asus TUF Gaming Z790-PLUS motherboard (just to have the latest chipset), without any problem. The price is high and what's more it is delivered without a cooler. Bad point from Amazon... Delivery was done securely (with a code to give to the delivery person) but the packaging was non-existent (an envelope). I clearly saw that the box containing the processor had "suffered" the hardships of delivery, but the main object was not damaged. I knew it was heating up quite a bit, so for the first time I installed watercooling for the processor. In this case a Thermaltake Toughliquid 360 (provide the corresponding case for the internal dimensions). In normal use it does not exceed 35Â° and pushed during fairly demanding gaming sessions (Cyberpunk 2077 / Forza Horizon 5...) we have a very reasonable temperature of less than 60Â°. I remember that my old i5 mentioned above could go up to +80Â° (with a slight overclock of +15%). I took the K version (and not KF) for two reasons: - The possibility of overclocking it very easily with the Asus motherboard, without exceeding reasonable limits (and therefore extending its useful life) - use it in case the graphics card breaks down (which happened to me precisely when I had the GTX1080... The maintenance and the Asus Chipset Z790 / RTX 4080 combination is perfect. The whole thing goes together perfectly... and is very expensive (!!!). However, no regrets, 4K display at all levels now!

ProductTitle: Intel Core I7-13700K Processor 30M Cache, Up to 5.40 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewContent: I built myself a new PC and it was definitely the right decision that I bought this IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i7-13700K desktop processor 16 cores (8 P cores + 8 E cores) 30M cache, up to 5.4 GHz, the KF is a bit better than the K but not significantly, why did I choose the K? I thought about it for a long time, KF or K, but then I thought I'd buy the K because it has an integrated graphics unit, if the graphics card is defective I can switch to the processor and can still use my PC without a black screen, and nothing is more annoying than when the PC stays black. The CPU is installed on an MSI MAG Z790 Tomahawk WiFi motherboard, ATX - supports Intel processors of the 12th and 13th gen, LGA 1700 - 90A SPS VRM, DDR5 Memory Boost 7200+MHz/OC, PCIe 5.0 & 4.0 x16,4 x M.2 Gen4, Wi-Fi 6E. The CPU is cooled by an MSI MAG CORELIQUID 240R V2 AIO water cooling CPU kit. It takes me exactly 16 seconds to boot up the PC, I measured the time. Thanks to the pump, the temperature of the CPU stays between 40 - 43 degrees in normal mode. In gaming mode it fluctuates between 73 and 84 degrees. The temperature does not get any higher. You can measure with the free program HWMonitor, the program measures all temperatures in the PC, CPU, GPU, RAM, hard drive, fan, etc. The IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i7-13700K processor is currently ranked 8th. The KF is ranked 7th in the ranking Guys, all I can say is, if you're building a new PC, don't cut corners in the wrong place, it's a hefty price (I paid 408 euros) but it's definitely worth it for me, a clear recommendation to buy Very important, the processor only runs really well under Windows 11, no idea why, I read that it only reaches its full, how should I put it, full potential under Windows 11. But Win 11 is really, well, I won't say anything about that .......

Well, after numerous stress tests, I discovered that once the MCE (multicore enhancement) function has been activated in the BIOS on both, the I7-13700 performs slightly stronger than its "big brother" 13700K which instead gains very little with MCE active. Among other things, the latter heats up even more, so I preferred to return the 13700K and keep the smooth 13700 which also costs around thirty euros less.

ProductTitle: Intel Core I7-13700K Processor 30M Cache, Up to 5.40 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewContent: The most common problem with these are that they run too hot, and I didn't quite understand the severety of this until I've started using this CPU. On CBR24 you can easily hit 100*C and above without any modifications, this is not great but Intel claims that the thermal throttle happens at 105*C so anything below that number is "fine". I think most people are not comfortable with temps that high and considering I'm using a 360mm AIO I don't imagine 100*C is acceptable in any scenario. In any case, undervolting is really worth it. I've set my undervolt in XTU to be at 0.085V and my temps are maxing at about 85*C which is much better. I've not really pushed it hard yet with games or other software so some of that is yet to be tested but so far I think performance is good, and for the money I think it's worth it. Perhaps Ryzen is catching up but I think Intel takes the edge on this CPU.

The unlocked nature of this processor caters to overclocking enthusiasts, allowing for fine-tuning to extract every ounce of performance. This feature is complemented by Intel's advanced cooling technologies, ensuring stable temperatures even under heavy workloads. Gaming experiences are taken to new heights with the i7-13700KF, thanks to its high clock speeds and robust architecture. The processor effortlessly handles demanding games and applications, providing a smooth and immersive user experience. Multitasking becomes a breeze with the ample core count, enabling seamless execution of multiple applications simultaneously. Whether you're streaming, video editing, or running virtual machines, the i7-13700KF excels in handling resource-intensive tasks. The Intel Core i7-13700KF also supports the latest DDR5 memory technology, enhancing overall system responsiveness and data transfer speeds. In conclusion, the Intel Core i7-13700KF Gaming Desktop Processor is a stellar choice for users who demand uncompromising performance. Whether you're a gamer seeking high frame rates or a content creator requiring processing power, this unlocked processor is a worthy investment that brings your desktop experience to a whole new level.

ProductTitle: Intel Core i7-13700KF Gaming Desktop Processor 16 cores (8 P-cores + 8 E-cores) - Unlocked
ReviewContent: The Intel Core i7-13700KF presents a compelling value proposition for its price. As part of Intel's 13th Gen "Raptor Lake" series, it boasts a robust 8 Performance-core (P-core) and 8 Efficient-core (E-core) configuration, mirroring the previous-gen flagship i9-12900K but at a more accessible price pointâ€‹â€‹. This configuration, coupled with updates like larger L2 caches for P-cores and improved cache hardware-prefetchers, contributes to its outstanding performance. In terms of raw performance, the i7-13700KF demonstrates commendable prowess. It outperforms the 12th gen flagship Core i9-12900K in single and multi-core tests, albeit marginally, and shows significant performance gains over its direct predecessor, the Core i7-12700K, with a 12% and 32.5% lead in single-core and multi-core tests, respectivelyâ€‹â€‹. When compared to competitors like the AMD Ryzen 7 5800X and Ryzen 9 5950X, the i7-13700KF shows a remarkable 23% and 25% single-core performance bump, and an even more impressive 67% and 15% lead in multi-core performance against these AMD chipsâ€‹â€‹. However, buyers should be aware that the Core i7-13700KF does not come with integrated graphics. For users who require onboard video capabilities, the slightly higher-priced Core i7-13700K would be the best choice. The absence of integrated graphics in the 13700KF model can be a significant consideration for those who don't plan to use a dedicated graphics card. The i7-13700KF stands out as an excellent choice for its price, offering high-end performance that rivals even some flagship models from the previous generation. Its value is particularly notable when considering its performance metrics against direct competitors and predecessors

I mention that game because for me, if i can run it stable, with a good amount of FPS, current patch performance issues not considered its what I wanted. my numero uno tip for you is - if you are getting HOT temps ... like 85C or close to that while gaming? you want to go turn off Intel adaptive boost technology in your bios.  research your board and see if you can undervolt. the intel fail safes that asus has setup on my board put voltage at 1.4+. using the asus typical setting its more like 1.2 or 1.3.  much cooler. and stable. also asus had long term load at the same wattage as short term. switched that back to intel spec and ... yeah its not as bad of an oven now. then look into improving your cooling. be nice if it was like not 100 bucks over the 13600 however.

ReviewContent: Keep in mind that the 13th gen processors are geared towards performance AND power consumption. When you look at the resource monitor you'll notice most threads are "parked" . If you prefer to run unparked - all threads playing at once - there are softwares out there that'll help you to achieve this. Perhaps Intel's Extreme Tuning Utility can achieve this for you. ReviewContent: I purchased this processor to replace my old i7 7700k which had completed its journey, so I must start by saying that the performance leap in my case was notable. But let's proceed in order: ðŸ“¦ Packaging and shipping: as always with Amazon, shipments arrived on time with packaging suitable for the product. It is Intel's practice to use cardboard boxes to contain their processors which obviously have their own hard plastic case (maybe just the i9s have another one, but I'm not sure). inside the box together with the product there is its own booklet and various documentation. âš™ï¸ Performance: a bomb. As already said, in my case my generational leap has certainly made the difference, but in any case we are talking about a high-level product. I use it both for gaming and for work (rendering, 3D modeling, graphics) and in both cases it allows for truly excellent results. A bit of a sore point (but up to a certain point), make sure you have an adequate dissipation system, since this little beast has a tendency to rise quite a bit with the temperatures if put under stress, so accompany it with a nice heat sink and a case well ventilated. âœ… Recommended: if you are looking for a high-level and above all versatile processor, this is for you. There are certainly better performing solutions, but you have to go for i9 (to stay in the Intel field) but the prices are adjusted accordingly. Personally, to date, I believe that i7 is still the best compromise between quality/price.

ReviewContent: Excellent processor for versatile professional/gaming use. However, for my part, only doing gaming; Above all, I was struck by its indecent consumption and its excessive heating compared to the competition (7800x3d). A fan of homogeneous PCs from a silence/temperature/performance point of view, my Noctua nhd15 unfortunately did not cool it sufficiently on CPU-intensive games, such as Battlefield 2042 or the latest Last of Us. The fans race and the processor then reaches indecent temperatures running around 80 degrees continuously, with peaks at 90Â°... With an Artic Liquid Freezer II 360, the result is more satisfactory, but still problematic if we compare to the competition. The aforementioned points, combined with the lack of scalability of the platform, I ultimately did not keep it and went with the Ryzen (my first AMD processor). Anyone who needs a versatile processor will, however, make the right choice by opting for this Intel... provided they have cooling proportional to the power of the CPU and regularly check that the processor does not heat up excessively.

ReviewContent: I upgraded my setup by replacing my i9-9900Kf with the i7-13700KF, which I paired with a Gigabyte Z790 Elite motherboard. For the cooling system, I kept the Corsair AIO Watercooling H100i Capellix Elite RGB 240mm that I already had. Regarding temperatures (with the H100i Capellix AIO): At rest: 34Â°C In-game: 47Â°C When testing with 100% CPU utilization: 63Â°C As a 3D graphic designer, when From a rendering test, temperatures vary between 74 and 76Â°C maximum. In other words, the temperature remains acceptable even with intensive use, as long as it does not exceed 85Â°C, beyond which it starts to get hot. I still made a slight modification to the BIOS without affecting the base frequency. I performed an undervolt in the BIOS with a Vcore Offset of -0.12, which allows me to gain a temperature drop of -7 to -8 degrees compared to the original settings. Overall, this is a very versatile and powerful processor, capable of handling gaming and application tasks with ease. So perfect for my mixed use as a Gamer and 3D Graphic Designer

ReviewTitle: Intel Core i7-13700KF: Perfect price-performance for first-class performance!
ReviewContent: The Intel Core i7-13700KF has revolutionized my gaming world, especially in an intense game like Escape from Tarkov. With this processor, I immerse myself in a whole new dimension of gaming experience. With an impressive clock speed of 5.4 GHz, I experience breathtaking gameplay, without any lag or stutter. In Tarkov, speed is crucial, whether it's precise aiming or lightning-fast reaction to enemy threats. The i7-13700KF allows me to master any situation with impressive speed and precision. But the i7-13700KF is not only a master of gaming, it is also an invaluable partner for video editing. Cutting, rendering and editing high-resolution material - even in 4K - is effortless and without any lag. This allows me to fully concentrate on the creative design of my projects. Thanks to the additional water cooling, the processor's performance remains consistently at the highest level, even during the most heated battles in Tarkov. I have the certainty that my system will work reliably even under the highest load. All in all, the Intel Core i7-13700KF is not just a processor, but a real game changer. It allows me to get the most out of "Escape from Tarkov" and take my video editing projects to a new level. This investment has definitely paid off. With the Intel Core i7-13700KF, video editing becomes a real pleasure. Even with high-resolution material and complex effects, the processor works effortlessly and without any delays. For me as a video editor, this means that I can fully concentrate on the creative design of my projects without being slowed down by technical limitations. The fast and precise processing of video material enables me to work more efficiently and complete my projects in less time. In addition, I can easily handle several tasks at the same time, which significantly increases productivity. The Intel Core i7-13700KF also shows its strengths when rendering videos. The high clock speeds ensure that rendering times are noticeably shortened. This not only means less waiting time, but also more time for creative details and perfecting my videos. Overall, the Intel Core i7-13700KF has far exceeded my expectations when it comes to video editing. It is an indispensable partner in my workflow and allows me to get the most out of my material. I am thrilled with the performance and efficiency that this processor offers.

ProductTitle: IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i7-13700KF Processor 30M Cache, up to 5.40 GHz
ReviewTitle: Heats up so much that you have to undervolt the processor...
ReviewContent: Bad performance for the price: big Intel marketing stunt and nothing more... It heats up so much that I have to "undervolt" the processor by -0.11v (Offset) in the BIOS of the ASUS Prime motherboard Z790-P Wi-Fi. Otherwise, the processor, under intensive load, goes into thermal breakdown and collapses the frequency of all cores. In short, a lot (too many) cores for not much and with a very hefty addition: to date, an i7-gen10 or 11, in real life (not in the Benches), does the same job with consumption and heat much lower... And I'm not even talking to you about the uselessness of the DDR5 that goes with it... Price multiplied by 2 for the same performance as DDR4... (this, always in real life, not in the benches!...) I came from an i7-2600K more than 10 years old and am really disappointed: Ok the system is faster, but it's not crazy either and for an exorbitant price ! I definitely don't recommend it. For me, this processor is a bad evolution of generation 12 which itself was already bad: in short, marketing chatter without any concrete interest.

ProductTitle: IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i7-13700KF Processor 30M Cache, up to 5.40 GHz
ReviewContent: On the one hand, Intel delivers a very fast CPU, but it is practically unusable out-of-the-box. The problem is the power consumption is far too high and the associated thermal problems. Even with a 360 AIO water cooler (bequiet Silent Loop 2), the CPU goes to over 100Â°C under load and is then automatically throttled. So in order to achieve a reasonably reasonable noise level, you have to undervolt in the BIOS (turn down the voltage) and limit the maximum power consumption. There are recommendations of 125W on the net, which limits the CPU's performance by around 10-15%. The funny thing is, if you set the power consumption to around 170-180W, you can even achieve more performance (e.g. Cinebench), because the CPU is then no longer throttled due to thermal problems. So if you want to play around in the BIOS and with Intel XTU to have a reasonably acceptable level after hours, you can try the experiment. If you just want to put it together and get started, you're better off buying a 13600 or AMD. Sorry, but that's not how you bring a product to market.

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewContent: I waited for this generation to upgrade my Generation 8 build which ran at 5100Mhz and now I'm simply happy with the performance of the i9-13900k processor which reached speeds of 6200Mhz in its settings (Attached image). I used an ASUS Z690-F card which did NOT recognize the memories (I used 64GB Corsair at 5200 MHZ), the machine simply would not boot and the orange light on the motherboard would stay on indicating DRAM problems, after reading a lot I found that it was necessary to update the BIOS from the rear FLASHBACK connection, once done the operation was correct and I have not had any major problems. I installed a 120mm cooler master lite radiator to control the processor since as incredible as it sounds the 360mm KRAKEN x73 was not able to keep the temperatures at bay. The 120mm Cooler Master keeps the processor without load or minimum load between 32 and 40 degrees and with maximum load and tests it hits 80 degrees, which is simply great considering that the maximum temperature of the Processor is 125 degrees, I placed 2 Noctua Fans at 3000 revolutions on the radiator in push / pull configuration. ReviewTitle: Gaming Powerhouse Unleashed: A Positive Review of the Intel Core i9-13900K Gaming Desktop Processor
ReviewContent: The Intel Core i9-13900K Gaming Desktop Processor has completely redefined my gaming and computing experience, offering a level of performance that's truly in a league of its own. With an impressive 24 cores, this processor delivers raw power that translates into seamless gaming, multitasking, and content creation. To start, the processing prowess of the Intel Core i9-13900K is jaw-dropping. The 24 cores and 48 threads make it a true powerhouse, capable of handling the most demanding tasks with ease. Whether it's immersive gaming, 3D rendering, video editing, or complex simulations, this processor doesn't break a sweat. The gaming performance is a standout feature. With its high clock speeds and multithreading capabilities, the i9-13900K ensures buttery-smooth gameplay even in the most graphically intensive titles. The ability to run background applications without compromising gaming performance is a game-changer for streamers and content creators. Multitasking reaches new heights with this processor. The 24 cores enable effortless switching between applications, ensuring a seamless workflow even with resource-hungry software. Whether I'm editing videos, running virtual machines, or working on complex projects, the processor's performance remains consistently impressive. The Intel Core i9-13900K's compatibility with the latest technologies is worth noting. Support for PCIe 5.0 and DDR5 memory allows for lightning-fast data transfer speeds and optimal memory performance, further enhancing the overall computing experience. Thermal management is another area where this processor shines. The advanced cooling solutions and efficient power consumption ensure that the processor maintains optimal temperatures under heavy loads, contributing to its long-term reliability. In conclusion, the Intel Core i9-13900K Gaming Desktop Processor has exceeded my expectations in terms of performance, gaming prowess, multitasking capabilities, technology integration, and thermal management. Its 24 cores offer a level of processing power that's perfect for gamers, content creators, and professionals seeking exceptional performance across the board. If you're looking to elevate your gaming and computing experience to unprecedented heights, the Intel Core i9-13900K is undoubtedly a worthy investment. It has earned my highest praise and has become the centerpiece of my high-performance desktop setup.

ReviewTitle: An Expensive Powerhouse: Intel Core i9-13900K
ReviewContent: The Intel Core i9-13900K is undeniably a top-tier processor that showcases unparalleled performance and technological excellence. However, it's essential to acknowledge that this exceptional power comes with a premium price tag. While the Intel Core i9-13900K may be considered expensive, the performance it delivers makes it a compelling option for those who demand the absolute best from their computing experience. Let's address the elephant in the room first: the cost. The i9-13900K is indeed one of the higher-priced processors on the market. This means it may not be the most budget-friendly choice for all users, especially for those whose computing needs aren't as resource-intensive. However, for professionals, enthusiasts, and gamers who rely on cutting-edge performance to tackle demanding workloads and push their creativity to the limits, the i9-13900K's price begins to justify itself. With its impressive 16 cores and 32 threads, this processor shines in multitasking scenarios and content creation tasks. Video rendering, 3D modeling, and heavy computation become swift and seamless experiences, reducing project turnaround times and boosting overall productivity. Gaming enthusiasts will be delighted with the i9-13900K's prowess in delivering breathtaking gaming performance. Its native support for DDR5 memory and PCIe 5.0 ensures faster data access and transfer, leading to quicker load times and smoother gameplay, which enhances the gaming experience to a whole new level. The processor's unlocked multiplier empowers overclockers to maximize its potential further, catering to those who love to tweak and fine-tune their systems for optimal performance. With Intel's Turbo Boost Technology 4.0, you'll experience intelligent performance adjustments, optimizing efficiency when required and delivering maximum power when needed. Furthermore, Intel's 10nm SuperFin process technology contributes to the i9-13900K's energy efficiency, ensuring that it provides a balance between power and consumption, which is especially vital for environmentally-conscious users. In conclusion, the Intel Core i9-13900K may have a higher price point, but it delivers a level of performance that leaves competing processors trailing in its wake. While not everyone might find it within their budget, for those seeking the absolute pinnacle of computing capabilities, the i9-13900K is an investment worth considering. If performance and cutting-edge technology are your top priorities, this processor will undoubtedly elevate your computing experience to new heights, making it a worthy 5-star choice despite its cost.

ReviewTitle: Will be dead on arrival or degrade over months
ReviewContent: My first review ever. Intel has finally acknowledged this issue, search "Regarding Reports of 13th/14th Gen Unlocked Desktop Users Experiencing Stability Issues" on google. For me, worked great for about a month, then slowly started experiencing stability issues. Games would crash and get an occasional blue screen. After about 6 months, there were noticeable stability issues, with many games unable to boot past main menu, causing blue screen on launch, or experiencing frequent crashes. Friends in separate friend groups would always comment on my computer issues, showing bugs and crashes that have no apparent causes. After a year, my PC can only run super smash brothers melee with stability and even chrome tabs are crashing now. Discord has to be run on chrome because the app crashes every 10 seconds, I can't play any games. I had dedicated tens of hours into investigating only to realize it's been the CPU all along. I also had to upgrade my motherboard to accommodate this CPU and now I have to investigate if this CPU has caused irreparable damage to the motherboard. I expect Intel will be facing heavy financial losses due to influx of warranties as the issues become more and more public. Please look up "Intel 13th and 14th Gen stability" for more info, or "Intel Raptor Lake stability" on Google for further cases. Unacceptable for a company worth over $100B to push out a product like this.
Author: Erik Gerlitz

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewTitle: Amazing processor, but check your CPU power management in BIOS
ReviewContent: So, first thing's first. This is a genuinely powerful CPU that's been able to handle basically every task that I've thrown at it. It runs demanding tasks like encoding and gaming with ease. Now with that out of the way; Thermals. This thing gets hot, and I mean REALLY hot. If you're going with air cooling I strongly recommend a double tower, six/eight pipe Air cooler like the Corsair A115 or a Cooler Master MA824. If you are going the AIO route, anything LESS than a 360mm AIO will under perform. For that, go with any 360mm AIO from any brand of your choice. If you have the space, go with a 420mm AIO for the best results. Finally, there has been recent reports of CPU degradation and instability when using this CPU. I am using this with an asus ROG STRIX Z790-H motherboard and it basically JUICED the CPU like no tomorrow until I applied intel's Power settings for this CPU. This likely is the cause of the degradation. Be sure to check intel's website for recommended power settings. Also check your motherboard vendor for any bios updates as Intel has confirmed that many motherboard vendors are running the i9 13900k CPU out of intel's specifications. In conclusion here's my personal experience: The CPU functions, but I can not use Asus' AI Overclocking feature as I get a BSOD with the CLOCK_WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT error and apps will randomly crash. You probably shouldn't use any AI assisted overclocking feature if you can help it. Even running this at stock, there is still a substantial amount of performance in this CPU. If you have an older rig and are looking to upgrade your CPU, I would just wait for Meteorlake or just go with AMD. Final note: I am not using a contact frame on my motherboard for my CPU.
Author: Carlos Canales

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewTitle: Works, but with needed system configuration
ReviewContent: I initially got a 13700K, but grabbed this after and snubbed the 14 gen. I upgraded from 8700K, ***which is still a very capable cpu even today, but due to the demands of certain programs the 13900K is handling them better than the 13700K so far. Fingers crossed to hoping it will not fail in future. There are well documented power issues that Intel and their partners have with the 13th, 14th gen. May be an upsell to the upcoming ultra line of cpus? So you have to take this into account and modify your motherboards bios, and follow Intel's suggested settings. I will update this review if anything come up.

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewTitle: Surprisingly Fast but watch out for corner chip escapes
ReviewContent: We set up multiple computing servers to run heavy video processing algorithms essentially continuously everyday - to make a long story short, we liked how fast this ran compared to the i7-11th gen we had from before. The surprising thing is one day among 8 essentially identical machines, we noticed one desktop that seemed much hotter than the others.  We hooked up measurement of power draw and temperature readings of the CPUs and was shocked that this one was drawing 450W as others were showing < 200W.  And temperature went up to 100C while the others were at 70C. One system had a glitch where if you ran python and import numpy, it would reboot.  We determined the problem was that PSU only supported +12V rail at 20A.  We switched to a 600W PSU that supports +12V @50A and it worked flawlessly.  So watch out that your PSU supplies sufficient amps at +12V. Ordered a replacement, replacement brand new would not boot up.  We swapped back old CPU from, and it boots up but runs hot again.  This one we had to reduce workload to 75% of other systems to cool it down. So 2 out of 10 desktops are defective  This is a huge surprise.  These systems had no GPU, only motherboard, 64GB of DDR5, and an SSD.  Has anyone else seen this?
Author: IndyToronto

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewTitle: The best CPU I have ever had, and good price, too.  But beware of Z690 motherboards
ReviewContent: I got this and a new DDR5 motherboard with Z690 chipset.  It didn't boot when I set it all up.  It turns out the Z690 needs a BIOS update to work with this CPU.  Luckily I had an older i7 that worked on this motherboard.  I dropped it in and it booted, then I did the BIOS update.  After that it boots this CPU just fine. Before this I was a die-hard AMD supporter.  I had 5950x with 16 cores, 32 threads, and 72MB of cache.  But, it just doesn't compete with this i9.  I haven't tried the 7950x, but I read that the P-cores just blow away the AMD cores.  Even with less cache.  The setup of 8 performance cores, and 16 efficiency cores just works.  It stays much cooler than earlier i9's and the AMD.  I use a water cooler, but it's not required.  Nothing slows this down when paired with DDR5. I wish the AMD was better, I like the company more.  But, I want the best of the best, and as of today there is nothing better than this available.  If you game, or do graphics, or anything on your PC this is the CPU for you.  It will NOT disappoint. A word on the X790 chipset.  You would think they will have better performance because they are newer.  They don't.  They will work with the i9 no matter what, while the Z690 might need a BIOS update.  They have one more USB port.  But otherwise there is no benefit to getting Z790 and they cost a LOT more.  So, if you have the ability to use an older CPU to flash the bios, or find one that is new enough that it doesn't need the update, this CPU will be great.

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewTitle: Great CPU and Really Fast Will Not Overheat If You Set It Up Correctly
ReviewContent: I really like this CPU and it has worked well for my needs. Many had the issue of overheating, throttling and even bending in some instances. I have not experienced any of this since I knew exactly what settings needed adjusted in the BIOS to keep this monster CPU running cool. It seems that motherboard manufacturers tend to turn these up way past their limits by default and that was what caused all the issues. All you need to to is look up the specs for your CPU and setup the BIOS of your motherboard accordingly. I am using the Aorus Waterforce X 280 with Artic MX-6 Thermal Paste just in case you are curious. This has also been installed on the GIGABYTE Z790 AORUS Elite AX motherboard. As long as you set this up correctly you will not have any issues and will get a great performing CPU.

I've had it for about 4-5months now, before it started cooling off outside I was have to crank the A/C to keep my gaming room cool and now that its cooling off outside (30-40 f at night) I have blocked off the vents in the room to prevent any additional heat.  This thing paired with a RTX 4090 keeps this room plenty warm enough for me!  So on the plus side, I'll be saving on heating this winter!!

ProductTitle: Intel Core i9-13900K Desktop Processor LGA 1700 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz'
ReviewContent: I bought two of these from Amazon after one from another vendor failed to POST.  Both worked the first time.  Do you need 24 cores for games?  Most games use 4 or 6 cores max, so probably not.  Video editing can benefit from the extra cores.  Intel supports XMP (extreme memory profile) and this processor is unlocked (it can be overclocked).  Overclocking increases the power consumption and heat; therefore, one needs a robust cooling solution.  Overclocking can void your warranty which is strange since Intel allows and even promotes overclocking with the Intel Extreme Tuning Utility.  I have the NZXT Kraken x 73 RGB liquid cooler.  With the NZXT CAM software you can see the CPU (and GPU) temperatures and control the fan speeds, reducing the risk of damaging the processor.  While idling (at 5.5 GHz) the CPU temperature is 30 C.  Under a 50% load or overclocked the temperatures are below 60 C.  Pros: Good for video editing Cons: A bit pricey for a gaming computer.  Don't overclock without monitoring temperatures to keep below 60 C.

I would also recommend a large radiator too, 3 fan coverage. This thing is an excellent space heater. Outclasses thread ripper by almost double its paces per benchmarking in multicore. Handles everything I throw at it then yawns at me as if it was boring and mediocre work. Simply put, leader of the pack right now and handles literally anything Iâ€™ve tried to hit it with, even running multiple games at once (when combined with a good GPU, naturally). I have zero complaints. Iâ€™ve learned to hate a lot of intel items over the years, but this truly is a marvel.

ReviewTitle: Worst warrenty support i have ever delt with or it doesnt support windows 10 or 11.
ReviewContent: It worked fine for 6 months, then i start running into Error Code 0xC0000005 with lots of various applications in Windows 11.  I figure it was after an update and they turned on some security thing, and I dissabled all the security stuff and still running into issues.  I reset the OS, still issues, I do a fresh clean install, still issues.  I try replacing the memory, still issues.  I try installing win 11 with a different boot installer, still issues.  I try windows 10.... still issues.  I try reinstalling it 2 more times, still the same issue. I decide to go to Micro Center to have them diagnose the issue, while i am there, their windows 10 install crashes with the same error code.  They take it in, and in 2 days message me saying its the CPU.  They tried the CPU in a different motherboard and the issue still shows up.  So, i go and pick up the machine. I try to file a warrenty claim with Intel, but their login system was broken for a week, so I had to chat with a support person.  We spend 1 hour typing about the issue.  I send him screenshots of the CPU itself, the text from Microcenter, the recepit from Amazon, screenshot of the Bios showing all my hardware information, a screenshot of the recepit from microcenter, a screenshot of the error code. I wait a week or so, i can finally log into Intel website, and i dont see a support ticket.  I open up chat again,  i tell them my ticket and they tell me that it wasnt assigned to an email address.  They assign it and forward the support response to me. And the response says, they cant contact Microcenter to confirm it.  And that its not a CPU issue anyways because that code is due to an OS issue. An OS issue.  I ask them to reiterate their point, because if its an OS issue, that means they dont believe me and Microcenter.  I also pointed out again that i have installed Windows 10 and 11 at least 5 times.... and they respond with, i need documentation from Microcenter.  So, they dont believe me and they believe this is an OS issue still. It has been 11 days and they wont move forward unless I send the documentation from Micro Center now. Works great, but hope you never have to file a warrenty claim because its going to take at least a month and thats if your lucky.
Author: Zev

This processor is designed to benefit more advanced users so I'd save the 150$ and get the cheaper 13700k. Also this processor is notoriously hot, so a beefy noctua air cooler or preferably a 280mm+ watercooler AIO is necessary (especially for overclocking).

This has literally been the most difficult processor to reign in heat I've had to deal with in my 30 years of computing, AMD is starting to look good I guess (which is why I switched to and have remained with intel for 20 years, AMD ran hot back in the day). Apparently even the 14900k's are having issues. ProductTitle: IntelCore i9-13900KF Desktop Processor 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz' Socket LGA 1700
ReviewContent: The Intel Core i9-13900KF, the latest-gen gaming desktop processor, is nothing short of a powerhouse when it comes to delivering unparalleled performance for gamers and enthusiasts alike. With 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) and unlocked overclocking potential, it redefines what you can expect from a gaming processor. Performance (â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…): The Intel Core i9-13900KF is an absolute beast when it comes to performance. With its combination of P-cores for high single-threaded performance and E-cores for multi-threaded tasks, it effortlessly handles anything you throw at it. Whether you're gaming, streaming, or running resource-intensive applications, this processor delivers smooth and lag-free performance. Overclocking (â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…): If you're an overclocking enthusiast, this processor is a dream come true. Being unlocked, it provides you with the flexibility to push its limits further. With proper cooling and tweaking, you can extract even more performance, making it a top choice for those who love to fine-tune their system. Gaming (â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…): Gaming with the Intel Core i9-13900KF is a sublime experience. It excels in delivering high frame rates and low latency, ensuring you get the most out of your gaming sessions. It handles modern AAA titles with ease, and thanks to the E-cores, it can handle background tasks like streaming without breaking a sweat. Thermal Design (â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…): While this processor is a powerhouse, it's important to note that it can generate significant heat when pushed to its limits. To fully unleash its potential, investing in a high-quality cooling solution is essential. A well-cooled system will ensure the CPU operates at its peak performance without thermal throttling. Value for Money (â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜†): There's no denying that the Intel Core i9-13900KF comes with a premium price tag. However, for those who demand the absolute best in gaming and multitasking performance, it's worth every penny. It's an investment in a system that will remain relevant and powerful for years to come. Compatibility (â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜†): It's important to note that this processor requires a compatible LGA 1700 motherboard, which may necessitate a motherboard upgrade if you're coming from an older system. Additionally, it doesn't include integrated graphics, so a dedicated graphics card is a must. In conclusion, the Intel Core i9-13900KF is a game-changing gaming desktop processor that sets new standards in performance and overclocking capabilities. Its 24 cores, unlocked nature, and exceptional gaming prowess make it a top choice for gamers and enthusiasts who demand the best. While it comes at a premium price, the investment is justified by the unparalleled performance and future-proofing it offers. If you're looking to build the ultimate gaming rig, the Intel Core i9-13900KF should be at the top of your list.

ReviewContent: Best investment I ever made when it comes to a gaming/streaming pc. Iâ€™m a pretty hardcore gamer and this cpu is the most amazing thing Iâ€™ve ever had when it comes to a high end build. I paired it with a rtx 4080 and needless to say this cpu doesnâ€™t disappoint. Now, this review isnâ€™t about pricing because we all know this cpu is expensive and honestly if youâ€™re only gaming then maybe a 13600k would suffice. However, if you are streaming, photo editing, video editing etcâ€¦. Then this is the right cpu for you. Iâ€™m able to snap together YouTube videos in seconds NOT minutes or anywhere near it. Iâ€™m able to stream and game at the same time with less than a 10 fps loss while gaming and streaming on the highest quality settings. My wife loves it for photo editing bc everything is just perfect. Only downside is that it does run hot but you can get a good 240-360mm aio that will tame this cpu with ease. All the issues I use to have on the 10th gen platform are completely irradiated now that I own this cpu. I did go with the ddr5 and honestly for me it runs better than ddr4. Tech reviewers say otherwise but from personal experience ddr5 is the future NOW. Performance issues I use to have with ddr4 and weaker cpus are just gone now. I can do so much and this cpu doesnâ€™t break a sweat. For instance, ddr4 for whatever reason sometimes wouldnâ€™t work with xmp although it was advertised. I like to tinker so it wasnâ€™t an issue BUT sometimes itâ€™s just nice to do a single click and let it dial itself in and thatâ€™s what ddr5 has done for me. Iâ€™ve used several different sticks with this cpu and from all of them I went with Corsair vengeance. Honestly, this is the most bada$$ cpu Iâ€™ve ever owned or seen in a personal system of mine. If you have the money I couldnâ€™t recommend it enough. Everybody has different needs and in my case I needed this cpu. It hasnâ€™t disappointed. As for amd, if you want the bugs and issues go ahead and grab one of those cpus and tell me how that goes. This cpu can do everything and more. Hope this review helps anybody who is on the edge about getting this or something else.

ProductTitle: IntelCore i9-13900KF Desktop Processor 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz' Socket LGA 1700
ReviewContent: i upgraded from 5900xt. I got the msi board z690 -a for 159, and this the 13900kf. I â€˜ve been wanting a cpu with an IGPU for years, but couldnâ€™t justify the price increase on the gpu version. I actually use a dgpu but it really is convenient, and they can be used to accelerate some work. Again, before you judge i'm using this for work, productivity. NOT gaming. I would spend 200 for a gaming cpu. my use case is productivity. iâ€™m a developer, and this is the sole reason i upgraded. I was fighting windows freezing and slowing down during a lot of my workflows. I use wsl intellj, docker, react apps java etc, often at the same time. Itâ€™s pretty noticeable the improvement. It really helped.  Like that i could use ddr4 for now since the boards are about 150 it was acceptable. Heat: The cpu gets a bad reputation due to heat and wattage. I put this in the bucket frankly that amd got as well. I mean itâ€™s fine they are using as much power as needed to maximize perf. I limited the cpu to 250w, and it runs on a d15 cooler than my 5900, Full load can get up to high 80c, but working is 30â€™s. you lose very little perf by running it more in the zone. I don't know about other boards but that msi one sure makes it easy and the price if right. About the cpu: it has a ton of cores, I didn't need to buy ddr5--  i need quite a lot of ram and it still costs too much for the benefit it provides in my workload. The memory controller on 13gen is far better than ryzen 5000 series. I couldn't before get my ddr4 stable at 4000 on the 5900x and it did it on the intel one immediately. Indeed i was even able to tighten up the timings just a touch. So modern processors (and i'd assume the amd ones as well) have made welcome improvements to memory support. Id' say if you don't need as much ram say 32gb, and you don't have ddr4 already to tide you over i'd consider getting ddr5 though.  I mean nothing is cheaper than what you have and 4k speed is fine. If i had nothing or maybe some old ram i'd go w/ ddr5. Price: For 570 itâ€™s decent deal here. It is more than i love spending, but for what you get it is a lot better than what amd is offering at the time i write this which was 700. I do wish intel supported board reuse down the line, but that even can. be overblown (to an extent, and only an extent) though it's a selling feature to me frankly reuse!! I had to really think about that. I don't understand why intel is so stubborn on this subject.  with my amd cpu i went from 2700x to 5900x and the board went from a 470 to 570 because i waned more io and better pcie but i also gave that board to my kid and upgraded it one time. With intel especially I mean i just buy cheap boards anyway and upgrade more because there are a ton of features that get added half the time. I usually try to spend about 150 on a board, though it. is getting harder but it would be more my preference. I 'm not really onboard with the 600 motherboards. Is there a  300 one in-between i guess so but that's equally unappealing to me esp w/ out the upgrade. Tips/A rant if you will: trust me on this that msi board for 159 is so amazing. It really works great. donâ€™t worry about the vrm. thatâ€™s also very overblown too. you can go calculate the amperage this will not come close. ALso msi is a great brand and the bios is easy to navigate. If you want fancy audio buy a dac that you can reuse and plug into usb and keep reusing it. Just think about what you really need in there. The msi board has a nice selection of pcie slots and well placed nvme. I use multiple gpu one nvidia gpu quatro for encoding (its a small one) and and amd one 6900 i bought for 570 for gaming. I just really love the layout connectivity and features of the board. They cut all the stuff i don't need and pared with the cpu it's all together about 700 for a cpu and board, pretty much as good as you can get.

ProductTitle: IntelCore i9-13900KF Desktop Processor 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz' Socket LGA 1700
ReviewContent: Cinebench R23 scores: 40,345 MT / 2,284 ST Upgrading from the Ryzen 5950X, this processor has some significant uplift, particularly in the single-core speed. Minimal overclocking headroom as Intel has already milked 90% of the performance on stock settings. However, with some tweaking, you're likely to get up to 6.2 Ghz boost behavior for single-core loads, and bump up the all-core boost to 5.7 Ghz (up from 5.5 Ghz stock). With some further tweaking of the voltage-frequency curve, you could probably tweak this even further. I'm not a big fan of all-core overclocks on these type of processors, as you will lose the boosting single-core speed. In my opinion, this processor shines for gaming because of its single-core boosting performance. Memory controller has been significantly improved over Alder Lake. I was easily able to get my DDR5 6400 XMP profile running without any tweaking. I'm pretty sure this can be easily pushed further, but it seems like around 6400 Mhz memory is the roughly the sweet spot in terms of price vs performance. Very power hungry, but despite the bad reputation from reviewers, the power consumption can be easily tamed. If you run power limits unlocked, you will likely be thermal limited due to thermal throttling at 100c. However, you don't need unlocked power limits - you're talking about a very small 5-10% performance uplift but using >100W more power to achieve this. I would suggest running it at stock power limits, or unlocked power limits but seriously consider undervolting. On a final note, I wouldn't consider getting the rumored 6.0 Ghz version of the 13900K in the future. The current 13900K can easily be pushed to >6 Ghz boost speeds and will save you money.

ProductTitle: IntelCore i9-13900KF Desktop Processor 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz' Socket LGA 1700
ReviewContent: Concerning Intel Core i9-13900KF, I have this CPU with board ASUS ROG Strix Z790-E Gaming WiFi 6E LGA 1700 for gaming usage.  Once I discovered that I had to slow the memory down from the 6600MHz XMP rating to 6200MHz, the board/cpu combo has worked very reliably  (multiple passes of OCCT Gold stress test).  Just checking the XMP II box,  the 6200MHz box and the (so called) AI overclocking box in the bios gives a score of 40K on Cinebench R23 so it's plenty fast -- the loss of 400MHz memory bandwidth isn't a big deal.  I tried various other adjustments but the latter turned out to be sufficiently fast and very reliable.  My current chip has a Silicon Predictor(SP) of 99 (roll of the dice).  I suspect that higher SP levels while possible are rare. I am using a ARCTIC Liquid Freezer II 360  AIO which works OK but the CPU can run hot.  The mother board cooling prediction for said AIO is 155 but that is not really enough for this chip to run all out.  It is easy to get this CPU up to 100C using OCT Power Stress test.  While the CPU might run at 100C for a long time, it will not do it any good and it will not run reliably -- I needed to check the 90C max box in the bios to get it to pass the OCCT power stress test.  I have a RTX 4090 and in the OCCT power test the net system power gets up to 1100W.  Normal gaming so far never gets to such power levels but still worth considering. FWIW, I have had a CPU apparently fail from running the OCCT Power Stress test.  If you want to run this CPU all out with reasonable temps, you really need significant cooling.  I doubt any AIO will work for this.  I suggest an open loop system with something like a Watercool MO-RA3 420 PRO radiator. All said, If you are building a gaming system, you would be just as well served with a ASUS ROG Strix Z690-E and a i9-12900KF CPU.  It will be easier to cool and will save you some money for a better graphics card which will make *much* more difference in most games than the CPU.

ProductTitle: IntelCore i9-13900KF Desktop Processor 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz' Socket LGA 1700
ReviewContent: It's fast, and works better than my space heater for keeping the desk undersides warm. Too warm, really. UPS says the computer is using 575 watts during the CPU stress test, about 175 watts at idle. TPU is 253w ... so with the 80%+ PS inefficiency, 300w makes sense. When using the 3080 GPU with the i9 CPU ... well, the heat coming from the case is similar to a 1000w space heater, really. Now reconsidering my choice for only an 850w PS. 1000w would probably be a better idea for this beast. As for speed. That's relative. But I am coming from an i9-7900x, and this is 3x faster, and it feels 3x faster. Memory is slower, (4ch vs 2ch) -- so I had to use DDR5-6400 to get a similar memory bandwidth. Lost some latency, but the overall effect is the thing still seems plenty fast. I dislike the way the CPU case instantly jumps to 100c -- no thermal mass what-so-ever in the CPU case. Or I have a bad CPU without whatever filler Intel puts between the die and the case. In any case, Intel needs to allow for more thermal mass to reduce these thermal stresses of instantaneous temp changes. Has to be stressing the silicon and lead to more thermal stress failures.

ReviewContent: Since I bought this processor, I have had nothing but trouble. I wish I'd just returned it, but I had rose-tinted glasses. It couldn't be Intel's fault, I mean, I've had dozens of intel CPUs over the years, and never had a problem. But this thing.... How do I know IT is the problem? When I set CPU affinity in Task Manager and limit the number of cores software has access to, everything runs fine. Slicing, games, my frigging web browser even! But if I unlock those applications and go 'all cores', stuf crashes left and right, the CPU bluescreens regularly, simple things like comfyUI crash the browser just by clicking on a node. HellDivers 2 can only be played between 2 and 10 minutes without crashing. All bets are off if I have 4 players. Just avoid this model. Get a different one or wait for the next iterationl.

ProductTitle: IntelCore i9-13900KF Desktop Processor 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) 36M Cache, up to 5.8 GHz' Socket LGA 1700
ReviewTitle: Check to make sure your board is compatible!
ReviewContent: This is my experience, I doubt that this is actually a problem with the processor itself, and more compatibility issue of the motherboard that I put it on, but I expected because it ran on 400 and 500 series motherboards that that meant that since mine is a 400 that it would run on it, I was wrong, the PC would not post when I put this processor on, I tried exchanging for another, and it did the same thing PC would not boot at all, it would go into a turn on then off then on then off then on then off then on then off cycle where nothing would actually show up on the monitor just my case fans would light up and then turn off and then light up and then turn off. So I don't know if the problem is with the processor or if I have a board compatibility issue, but I think I should not have had a board compatibility issue, and I have a 900 W power supply so there's no reason why there wasn't enough power to boot, I also used a liquid cooler so it should have had zero heat problems. I put a 12,900K on my motherboard from a 12700 KF which is what came with the computer, and the 12900K boots just fine. I am running a Lenovo legion t5 Gen 7. Should be compatible I don't see why it wouldn't be, but I have yet to try any other 13th generation processors to find out.

ReviewContent: These CPU's are throttled by temps & bottle necked by how good your CPU cooler is. Once 100 degrees is hit performance is throttled to maintain-but-not-exceed that temperature. A completely bottom-tier air-cooled noctua is sufficient to keep this CPU happy and you'd probably never know you're leaving some performance on the table. I upgraded from an 8th gen and the performance gain is huge.

Although baseline is about 33C on HWINFO, when using Cinebench -- it eventually starts thermal throttling after starting at 85C Peaks at over 360W, for just the CPU -- so this CPU needs a professional cooler, as the two fan cooler was working but just couldn't keep up with how insanely hot this thing runs. I tried using everything, from different thermal pastes and liquid metal -- all of which failed. Most people probably buy this CPU and have no idea that it's beeing throttled during benchmarking. I was sadened by all the posts on redit mentioning to undervolt or turn off multicore optimization, lol... Great CPU if you don't care about electricity and have a great cooler.

ReviewContent: I have now managed to tame this hothead somewhat on my Asus Rog Strix Z690 A-Gaming Wifi 4D. The previously installed BE Quiet dark rock Slim (180W TDP) was undersized for this, so I had to deactivate the standard Asus overclocking in the BIOS of my motherboard. Unthrottled, the processor consumed up to 283W. With the air cooler, it quickly went into thermal throttling. After I reduced the overclocking, it was only 243W. Only a few cores reached the temperature limit of 102Â°. Today I installed a BeQuiet silent Loop 2. The maximum temperature so far was 83Â°, I will test it in the gaming area then. It could be interesting again with Davinci Resolve.

ProductTitle: Intel Core I9-13900K Processor 36M Cache, Up to 5.80 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewContent: I installed this CPU a month or so ago now, alongside 64gb RAM, on an ASUS TUF Gaming Motherboard. The TLDR; It's lightening quick, and It's super easy to install. As with all CPU's care should be taken when installing and handling the CPU, but other than that it's relatively straight forward. All I have to say, is this CPU is a beast. Like its so overkill for the average user. In for gaming it is just overkill. It is the perfect CPU for me, but also for those who do intensive work loads, such as running running large data models for AI purposes. My particular use case for this CPU was to allow me to build a virtual lab to which I could analyse malware in an virtual sandbox, whilst also emulating real world hacking attacks. At present I am able to run several virtual machines with no performance issues. As you can probably imagine, this power hungry beast can get warm, but with an adequate cooling solution, there should be no issues in keeping the PC nice and cool.  I have paired this CPU with an AIO, and also additional fans for the case to ensure there is a lot of air flow to ensure that the thermals are a good temperature. My advice to anybody purchasing this CPU - go for it - it's well worth the investment, while at the same time you'll be future proofing your soon to be BEAST of a machine for the next 10 years.

Installation was absolutely fine and considering this was the first ever system I've built, so it demonstrates how easy it was to put into the motherboard if you just follow instructions to a tee. The H170I also comes with pre-applied thermal paste so I didn't even have to worry about that which was a bonus. and it's obviously doing its job at transferring all that heat. ProductTitle: Intel Core I9-13900K Processor 36M Cache, Up to 5.80 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewTitle: A monster with a big appetite!
ReviewContent: I knew what I was getting myself into. The 13900K is an absolute monster. Not just in terms of performance, but also in terms of power consumption and waste heat. I'll keep it short: Absolutely top for video work and rendering! Tons of computing power for software encoding and rendering. The Intel Quicksync encoder can render h.265 videos in 4K more than 3 times(!) faster than my 1080ti that I've used for this so far (with a 7700K that delivered about 80-90% of the performance of the 1080ti). There's nothing more to say about gaming. In current games, my 1080ti is constantly at its limit and the CPU gets bored, where the 7700K would otherwise have slowed everything down. Otherwise, there are enough reviews that show how much power is packed into this small piece of pressed technology. Now for the important points which I am not really criticising but just want to draw attention to: Yes, the power consumption and the waste heat are in a whole new league. Most gaming motherboards blast the CPU with voltage to ensure that everything is stable. But this processor cannot be cooled with that, no matter how good the CPU cooler is. It will ALWAYS reach 100Â°C due to the limit of the heat spreader. I use an Arctic Freezer II 280mm. I did three things to bring the temperatures under control: 1. Bought the Thermalright Contact Frame. I first used the original Intel mount and that immediately pushed me to the thermal limit. With the Contact Frame I immediately reduced the temperatures by 4-8Â°C per core and went from permanent thermal throttling to occasional hiccups in the temp throttle with Cinebench R23. 2. Undervolting. On the Asus Prime Z790-A I slowly lowered the core voltage using an offset while Cinebench was running. XMPII is activated. First in 0.02V steps until the blue screen and then I worked my way up. I was then stable in Cinebench at -0.135V, then later had a BSOD while gaming and now it is absolutely stable at -0.13V. CPU package power in Cinebench reduced from 310W peak power and 295W average to 270W peak power and 260W average in Cinebench. That brought the CPU down 10Â°C in the Cinebench 10min test. 3. Liquid Metal. Not really necessary but I wanted to get rid of a few more degrees to have enough reserves for the summer. Reduced the temperature by another 4-6Â°C. After these adjustments, I now have ALL cores in permanent turbo boost at 5.5GHz+4.3GHz, without throttling at 80Â°C peak single run Cinebench R23 and under 90Â°C in the endurance test with a fan curve tuned to quiet. WARNING: With these settings, the CPU is not stable in Prime95 and will crash the system! The loadline calibration must be set to level 5, but this will then bring the old power levels back. Undervolting is not suitable for every application. You then have to live with the 100Â°C limits if you don't want to use direct die cooling.
Author: Marc Hoffmann

ReviewContent: At the time of purchase, it is the top of the range from Intel in non-Pro CPUs. Nothing to say about the performances. ProductTitle: Intel Core I9-13900K Processor 36M Cache, Up to 5.80 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewTitle: Problems upon problems. Bluescreens in Windows 10 and 11
ReviewContent: The problems started on the first day. Windows would not install, but after a week of trying it suddenly worked. Then everything worked reasonably well for a while, with the occasional blue screen. Unfortunately, it then got worse and worse with image errors, programs closing and crashing. After that, everything was replaced one after the other. GPU, then RAM, SSD and the motherboard. The errors stopped again for a while and for over a month now, Windows 10 and 11 have not even started. Safe mode worked now and then if you clock the RAM down to 3000MHz. Windows 7 starts without problems (even though it shouldn't be running). The Intel Processor Location Test Tool found no errors. I kept searching and tested everything possible in the BIOS. I deactivated all P-cores except one and turned off all E-cores and Windows 10 and 11 started again. I kept testing even though it had already become clear to me that it had to be the CPU, so I activated all the E-cores again and everything worked. According to my theory, one of the P-Cores must be faulty. Replaced the CPU and everything is back to normal. Hardware: I9-13900K ProArt Z790-CREATOR WIFI RTX 3090 Strix Samsung 980 Pro SSDs Bluescreens: IRQL_NOT_LESS_OR_EQUAL APC_INDEX_MISMATCH KMODE_EXCEPTION_NOT_HANDLED KMODE_EXCEPTION_NOT_HANDLED nvlddmkm.sys ATTEMTED_EXECUTE_OF_NONEXECUTE_MEMORY DPC_WATCHDOG_VIOLATION KERNEL_SECURETY_CHECK_FAILURE SYSTEM TREAD EXCEPTION NOT HANDLED SYSTEM_SERVICE_EXCEPTION WdFilter.sys SYSTEM_SERVICE_EXCEPTION Ntfs.sys SYSTEM_SERVICE_EXCEPTION dxgkrnl.sys PAGE_FAULT_IN_NONPAGED_AREA IRQL_GT_ZERO_AT_SYSTEM_SERVICE DRIVER_IRQL_NOT_LESS_OR_EQUAL Programs DRIVER_IRQL_NOT_LESS_OR_EQUAL nvlddmkm.sys UNEXCEPTED_KERNAL_MODE_TRAP Reliability history: BEX BEX64 APPCRASH Damage caused to me through repairs ~2000â‚¬. I hope I could help someone who has the same problem.
Author: Felix

ProductTitle: Intel Core I9-13900K Processor 36M Cache, Up to 5.80 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewContent: The best processor in 2022-2023 for those who want to both game and work. Unfortunately, even with undervolting as efficiency it is a disaster, in gaming it consumes 3-4 times more than it should. When I watch a film every now and then the frequency jumps to the maximum, consuming 25-30 watts in Idle or almost, meh. I had to struggle to make custom energy profiles with QuickCPU to have acceptable consumption, but they are still inconvenient to change for each game and application, even with PowerPlanSwitcher. Windows is also to blame as it doesn't help, because it doesn't scale the frequency based on consumption. Then I also noticed that windows prefers to use the HT of the P-cores rather than the e-cores, increasing inefficiency and thus also causing performance drops since the logical cores are much less powerful than the efficient cores. As for overclocking there is nothing to do, the maximum to stay in PL2 and TMax 90Â° in full is 5.8Ghz on 2-3 cores, 5.7GHz on 7 cores and 5.5GHz on all P-cores, however setting it like this it becomes more inefficient with processes that require fewer cores. I've noticed that the CPU has a sweet spot at 5.3GHz where performance, efficiency and temperatures are much better, so one of the power plans I did with QuickCPU limits the clock to that frequency. The most positive thing is that compared to AMD it is possible to overclock the memory and increase performance by 10-15% in apps and games that use a lot of it and by doing so the CPU becomes more efficient given that the memories consume few watts and speed up computational performance and the difference with AMD's 3D VCache is bridged precisely in the applications in which it has the upper hand. To get this result I overclocked them to 6667 CL32 with the VDD safe at 1.435v and I lowered the secondary and tertiary timings, be careful that if you don't overclock properly you might not get any benefits, it's very stuff for geeks , between 4800 CL40 stock and 7200 CL34 stock will only change by 5%. As a test game at the end of the overclock I used Rust which is among the games that benefit most from fast RAM and cache and the difference is impressive, I went from 115 FPS with the stock XMP 5200 profile to 135 FPS with 6667 CL32. Probably with a high-end motherboard and RAM with dies that reach 8600MHz you can do better, but the important thing is the best compromise between frequency and timings. Don't get the F version because it's useless, it makes no sense to exist, the integrated GPU is worth â‚¬50, you pay almost nothing for it and when you need it it's always there ready, I connected the second monitor and Intel's Quick Sync to record and Processing videos is good, it consumes very little 1-10watts, it doesn't affect temperatures, you can deactivate it whenever you want and it is extremely useful even in the event of a failure of the dedicated one.
Author: Roenin

ProductTitle: Intel Core I9-13900K Processor 36M Cache, Up to 5.80 Ghz, LGA 1700
ReviewTitle: It consumes like a beast, costs a lot for what it offers (in December 2022).
ReviewContent: A dream processor, very fast, raw power.. but at a price. Actually two. because first you pay the processor its weight in gold, and probably for office or gaming use all this excess power is not necessary at all. And because during the life of the processor... you will pay dearly for the electricity bill... this little beast at full load consumes a minimum of 253 Watts (according to Intel specifications), but if your motherboard needs overclocking or it feels sbrex. .. it will also consume 300W .. as long as the heatsink keeps the processor below 100Â°C. Furthermore... you will need a heatsink with counter-flakes to dissipate 250-300 Watts of energy... and a normal 360 liquid AIO with 3 120 fans is not enough... it must be a heatsink with extra features to be able to keep below 100Â° the CPU is under stress and therefore do not let it go into thermal throttling. Probably a 13th generation i5 or i7 are more suitable for most users, and consume less power. as well as costing less. Also... if you plan to use a video card you might prefer the i9 13900f version, which does not include a GPU integrated into the processor. Why? Because many motherboards automatically disable the integrated IGPU if you have a real video card in your computer. so it would be money spent unnecessarily. If you also intend to use the IGPU in addition to the video card, consider purchasing a motherboard that allows the use of both GPUs.

ReviewContent: Best high end CPU for the money (as of time of writing this review, the 7950X3D is more expensive, not as widely available, and has strange gimmicks with Xbox Game Bar, so I avoided it). Despite all the news of it running extremely hot and hitting 300W, you can actually change this in your BIOS. On my Asus board, the default setting boosts it to ~310W for a short while causing 102Â°C on my 360mm Arctic AIO before dropping to something more reasonable. YOU CAN DISABLE THIS and enforce Intel stock 250W limits. Doing this led to no throttling and no crazy 100Â°C moments. This is not an inferno of a chip, your motherboard makes it one, so carefully check your BIOS settings if that bothers you! I'm happy that this chip does phenomenally in gaming and productivity both, so I can easily recommend it. (also, the packaging is pretty cool)

ProductTitle: IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i9-13900KF Processor 36M Cache, up to 5.80 GHz
ReviewContent: I had the opportunity to check out the Intel Core i9-13900KF processor, and here is my opinion on this incredibly powerful desktop chip: First of all, the spec sheet of this processor is impressive. With its 24 cores (made up of 8 P-cores and 16 E-cores) and 36 MB of cache, it offers exceptional computing performance. The maximum frequency of 5.8 GHz promises fast responsiveness for resource-intensive applications and games. This processor is aimed at the most demanding users, including content creators, performance-hungry gamers, and IT professionals. It is capable of handling intensive workloads thanks to its numerous cores and advanced multithreading technology. However, it is important to note that the price of this chip matches its exceptional performance. It is in the high-end range of processors, which may make it unaffordable for many users. In summary, the Intel Core i9-13900KF is a cutting-edge desktop processor that delivers unmatched performance for the most demanding tasks. If you're looking for exceptional processing power and price isn't a barrier, this chip is a solid choice. However, for users with more modest needs, there are more affordable options on the market.
Author: Fabien

ProductTitle: IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i9-13900KF Processor 36M Cache, up to 5.80 GHz
ReviewTitle: IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i9-13900KF: Reliable Performance with Adequate Cooling
ReviewContent: The IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i9-13900KF processor is a real powerhouse in terms of performance, but requires an adequate cooling system to get the most out of its potential. With 24 cores (8 P-cores + 16 E-cores) and a 36MB cache, this processor is designed to handle intense workloads and extreme multitasking. One of the main features of this processor is its reliability. Intel is renowned for the quality and reliability of its products, and the Coreâ„¢ i9-13900KF is no exception. However, it is important to note that given its high performance, it generates considerable heat during use. To optimize performance and ensure stable operation over time, I highly recommend pairing the processor with a good thermal paste, such as THERMAL GRIZZLY TG-KE-002-R, and a high-quality heat sink, such as DeepCool LT720 360 mm 4th Gen. These components will ensure effective heat dissipation and keep the CPU temperature under control even during the most intense usage sessions. In conclusion, if you are looking for reliable and powerful performance, the IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i9-13900KF processor is an excellent choice, but be sure to pair it with an adequate cooling system to ensure maximum performance and longevity of your system.

ReviewTitle: Die pure Kraft - IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i9-14900KF
ReviewContent: After upgrading my PC with the Intel Core i9-14900KF, I can say that this processor is a real powerhouse. Here are my impressions after extensive use: Performance: With its 24 cores and an impressive clock speed, the i9-14900KF delivers incredible performance. Whether it's gaming, video editing, or multitasking, this processor handles it all with ease. In games like Cyberpunk 2077 and Red Dead Redemption 2, the graphics run buttery smooth, even at the highest settings. Loading times are minimal, and gameplay is absolutely fluid. Multitasking: I often work with several demanding applications at once - from Adobe Premiere Pro to Photoshop to Blender. The i9-14900KF handles these tasks without breaking a sweat. Even when I'm rendering a video and working on a large photo editing project in another window at the same time, the system remains responsive and stable. Cooling: Speaking of cooling, the i9-14900KF can get quite warm under load. I opted for a high-quality water cooling system from NZXT (Kraken 360 Elite) to keep temperatures under control. With this AIO, the processor stays cool and quiet even during intensive gaming sessions or long rendering times. Value for money: The price of the i9-14900KF is certainly not low, but given the performance offered, I think it is justified. For enthusiasts and professionals who need maximum performance, this processor is a worthwhile investment. Conclusion: The Intel Core i9-14900KF is an absolute monster in terms of performance. Whether gaming, creative work or multitasking, this processor delivers consistently impressive results. The ability to overclock offers additional scope for performance enthusiasts. Even though it is a bit more expensive and requires good cooling, I am completely happy with my choice and can recommend the i9-14900KF to anyone who wants to get the most out of their system.

ProductTitle: IntelÂ® Coreâ„¢ i5-14600KF New Gaming Desktop Processor 14 cores (6 P-cores + 8 E-cores) - Unlocked
ReviewTitle: Running air cooled on DeepCool Assassin IV with ease
ReviewContent: So far so good.  This CPU is a monster and runs very nicely and boosts to max clocks (6ghz on two cores and 5.7ghz on all cores) unlimited TDP settings but thermally limited at 90c with -60mV offset.  I have noticed that it runs a bit cooler than my previous 13900KF, especially when you consider the core to core deltas.  I use my PC mostly for gaming and encoding, so as long as you have a great case with plenty of air flow and a top notch cooler, you can easily run it air cooled without issues as it will just throttle itself when it hits whatever thermal maximum you set in the UEFI BIOS. In gaming workloads it never throttles though and stays at 5.7ghz all core boost the entire time with temps in CPU intensive games anywhere from the upper 50s to mid 60s and upper 40s to mid 50s in non CPU intensive games **Update** I have the CPU now at 5.8ghz with HT disabled and a -75mV offset and it's working like a charm and very stable in gaming workloads and encoding (it downclocks when it hits 90c for encoding workloads but for gaming it stays at 5.8ghz), which is amazing since it's on an air cooled setup, though the setup is as optimal as it gets for air cooling!  As for temps, they are a little lower than running it at 5.7ghz with HT enabled and a -50mV offset.  If I use a -75mV offset with 5.8ghz and HT enabled, my PC crashes.  So disabling HT definitely enables the CPU to use less power. If you're predominantly using your machine for gaming, then I definitely recommend turning HT off regardless as most games tend to run better with HT disabled.  But if you're using it for productivity or a blend of both productivity and gaming, then definitely turn HT on. The only mildly disappointing thing for me is that the memory controller isn't as good as I thought it would be.  Mine runs 48GB DDR5 7400 CL34 at 1.35V on the IMC, but to hit DDR5 7600 CL36 with stability I need to increase the IMC voltage to 1.41V which just isn't worth it if you ask me for such a minor bump in performance.  My previous 13900KF could do 48GB DDR5 7800 at 1.36V on the IMC. Core wise though, the CPU is definitely superior to 13th gen.

ReviewTitle: The shipping method is still terrible.
ReviewContent: It arrived in a paper bag. Even though it's a very expensive precision device, the sloppy packaging is still a real turn-off. I really don't recommend buying precision devices like this on Amazon. When I bought the MB it came in a big paper bag. When I bought the memory it came in a paper bag. Of course the M.2 too. I bought it on Amazon because it was convenient, but I need to change my mind. If you have no choice but to buy it on Amazon, choose products that are sold directly by the manufacturer or shipped directly from the store. The user review is the 14geni7, which is the only one with improved performance from the 13gen. I use it with a 4070ti and it's comfortable for both work and games. I heard that the 14gen is the last i series, so I bought it. I'm going to install a GPU anyway, so I chose the F. I bought it on sale for about 10,000 yen cheaper and it's still cheaper than the K, so it's definitely a good deal. It's better to get it cheaper, so I strongly recommend allocating that budget to the GPU. It's helpful to have a graphics function when the GPU breaks down, but in my case, when the GPU broke down in the past, there was only so much the CPU could do, so I ended up not using the PC until I bought a new GPU. Making use of that experience, I have now purchased a spare GPU of around mid-range specs. The downside of having an F is that without a GPU, the BIOS, let alone the screen, won't turn on, so if you're building a new one or trying to build one for the first time, you need to think about the order in which you buy them to check the operation, so be careful about that. I'm satisfied with the product, but the shipping method is bad, so I'll give it 3 stars.
